    <section id="limits">
        <h2>Understanding Limits</h2>
        <p>Limits are the foundation of calculus. They help us understand how a function behaves as it approaches a specific point or infinity.</p>
        <h3>Key Topics:</h3>
        <ul>
            <li>Definition of a Limit</li>
            <li>One-Sided Limits</li>
            <li>Limit Laws</li>
            <li>Evaluating Limits Algebraically</li>
        </ul>
    </section>

    <section id="derivatives">
        <h2>Introduction to Derivatives</h2>
        <p>Derivatives measure the rate of change of a function with respect to a variable. They are essential for understanding motion, optimization, and change.</p>
        <h3>Key Topics:</h3>
        <ul>
            <li>Definition of the Derivative</li>
            <li>Rules of Differentiation</li>
            <li>Product, Quotient, and Chain Rules</li>
            <li>Implicit Differentiation</li>
        </ul>
    </section>

    <section id="integrals">
        <h2>Exploring Integrals</h2>
        <p>Integrals allow us to calculate areas under curves, volumes, and other accumulations. They are the reverse process of differentiation.</p>
        <h3>Key Topics:</h3>
        <ul>
            <li>Definite and Indefinite Integrals</li>
            <li>Fundamental Theorem of Calculus</li>
            <li>Integration Techniques</li>
            <li>Applications of Integration</li>
        </ul>
    </section>

    <section id="applications">
        <h2>Applications of Calculus</h2>
        <p>Calculus has vast applications in science, engineering, economics, and beyond. Learn how to use calculus to solve real-world problems.</p>
        <h3>Key Topics:</h3>
        <ul>
            <li>Optimization Problems</li>
            <li>Motion Along a Line</li>
            <li>Area Between Curves</li>
            <li>Volume of Solids of Revolution</li>
        </ul>
    </section>

